# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: managed-kubernetes
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:managed-kubernetes/cloud-native-computing] Cloud native techniques "enable loosely coupled systems that are resilient, manageable, and observable.
[src:managed-kubernetes/cloud-native-computing] Combined with robust automation, they allow engineers to make high-impact changes frequently and predictably with minimal toil." This independence contributes to the overall resilience of the system, as issues in one area do not necessarily cripple the entire application.
[src:managed-kubernetes/cloud-native-computing] Additionally, such systems are easier to manage, and monitor, given their modular nature, which simplifies tracking performance and identifying issues.
[src:managed-kubernetes/cloud-native-computing] The advantage of using containers is the ability to package all software needed to execute into one executable package.
[src:managed-kubernetes/cloud-native-computing] The container runs in a virtualized environment, which isolates the contained application from its environment.
[src:managed-kubernetes/container-orchestration] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:managed-kubernetes/container-orchestration] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:managed-kubernetes/container-orchestration] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:managed-kubernetes/container-orchestration] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:managed-kubernetes/container-orchestration] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:managed-kubernetes/container-orchestration] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:managed-kubernetes/container-orchestration] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:managed-kubernetes/container-orchestration] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:managed-kubernetes/container-orchestration] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] In network routing, the **control plane** is the part of the router architecture that is concerned with establishing the network topology, or the information in a routing table that defines what to do with incoming packets.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Control plane functions, such as participating in routing protocols, run in the architectural control element.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] In most cases, the routing table contains a list of destination addresses and the outgoing interface or interfaces associated with each.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Control plane logic can also identify certain packets to be discarded, as well as preferential treatment of certain packets for which a high quality of service is defined by such mechanisms as differentiated services.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Depending on the specific router implementation, there may be a separate forwarding information base that is populated by the control plane, but used by the high-speed forwarding plane to look up packets and decide how to handle them.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] In computing, the control plane is the part of the software that configures and shuts down the data plane.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] By contrast, the data plane is the part of the software that processes the data requests.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] The data plane is also sometimes referred to as the forwarding plane.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] The distinction has proven useful in the networking field where it originated, as it separates the concerns: the data plane is optimized for speed of processing, and for simplicity and regularity.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] The control plane is optimized for customizability, handling policies, handling exceptional situations, and in general facilitating and simplifying the data plane processing.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] A major function of the control plane is deciding which routes go into the main routing table.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] "Main" refers to the table that holds the unicast routes that are active.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Multicast routing may require an additional routing table for multicast routes.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Several routing protocols e.g., IS-IS, OSPF and BGP maintain internal databases of candidate routes which are promoted when a route fails or when a routing policy is changed.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Several different information sources may provide information about a route to a given destination, but the router must select the "best" route to install into the routing table.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] In some cases, there may be multiple routes of equal "quality", and the router may install all of them and load-share across them.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Routers forward traffic that enters on an input interface and leaves on an output interface, subject to filtering and other local rules.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] While routers usually forward from one physical (e.g., Ethernet, serial) to another physical interface, it is also possible to define multiple logical interfaces on a physical interface.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] A physical Ethernet interface, for example, can have logical interfaces in several virtual LANs defined by IEEE 802.1Q VLAN headers.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] When an interface has an address configured in a subnet, such as 192.0.2.1 in the 192.0.2.0/24 (i.e., subnet mask 255.255.255.0) subnet, and that interface is considered "up" by the router, the router thus has a directly connected route to 192.0.2.0/24.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] If a routing protocol offered another router's route to that same subnet, the routing table installation software will normally ignore the dynamic route and prefer the directly connected route.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] There also may be software-only interfaces on the router, which it treats as if they were locally connected.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] For example, most implementations have a "null" software-defined interface.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Packets having this interface as a next hop will be discarded, which can be a very efficient way to filter traffic.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Routers usually can route traffic faster than they can examine it and compare it to filters, so, if the criterion for discarding is the packet's destination address, "blackholing" the traffic will be more efficient than explicit filters.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Other software-defined interfaces that are treated as directly connected, as long as they are active, are interfaces associated with tunneling protocols such as Generic Routing Encapsulation (GRE) or Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS).
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Loopback interfaces are virtual interfaces that are considered directly connected interfaces.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Router configuration rules may contain static routes.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] A static route minimally has a destination address, a prefix length or subnet mask, and a definition of where to send packets for the route.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] That definition can refer to a local interface on the router, or a next-hop address that could be on the far end of a subnet to which the router is connected.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] The next-hop address could also be on a subnet that is directly connected, and, before the router can determine if the static route is usable, it must do a **recursive lookup** of the next hop address in the local routing table.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] If the next-hop address is reachable, the static route is usable, but if the next-hop is unreachable, the route is ignored.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Static routes also may have preference factors used to select the best static route to the same destination.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] One application is called a **floating static route**, where the static route is less preferred than a route from any routing protocol.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] The static route, which might use a dial-up link or other slow medium, activates only when the dynamic routing protocol(s) cannot provide a route to the destination.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Static routes that are more preferred than any dynamic route can also be very useful, especially when using traffic engineering principles to make certain traffic go over a specific path with an engineered quality of service.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] The routing table manager, according to implementation and configuration rules, may select a particular route or routes from those advertised by various routing protocols.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Different implementations have different sets of preferences for routing information, and these are not standardized among IP routers.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] It is fair to say that subnets on directly connected active interfaces are always preferred.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Beyond that, however, there will be differences.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Implementers generally have a numerical preference, which Cisco calls an "administrative distance", for route selection.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] The lower the preference, the more desirable the route.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Cisco's IOS implementation makes exterior BGP the most preferred source of dynamic routing information, while Nortel RS makes intra-area OSPF most preferred.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] If the route is "more specific" than an existing route, install it in addition to the existing routes.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] "More specific" means that it has a longer prefix.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] If the route is of equal specificity to a route already in the routing table, but comes from a more preferred source of routing information, replace the route in the table.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] If the routes are of equal metric and the router supports load-sharing, add the new route and designate it as part of a load-sharing group.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Typically, implementations will support a maximum number of routes that load-share to the same destination.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] If that maximum is already in the table, the new route is usually dropped.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] See forwarding plane for more detail, but each implementation has its own means of updating the forwarding information base (FIB) with new routes installed in the routing table.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] If the FIB is in one-to-one correspondence with the RIB, the new route is installed in the FIB after it is in the RIB.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] If the FIB is smaller than the RIB, and the FIB uses a hash table or other data structure that does not easily update, the existing FIB might be invalidated and replaced with a new one computed from the updated RIB.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Multicast routing builds on unicast routing.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] Each multicast group to which the local router can route has a multicast routing table entry with a next hop for the group, rather than for a specific destination as in unicast routing.
[src:managed-kubernetes/control-plane] There can be multicast static routes as well as learning dynamic multicast routes from a protocol such as Protocol Independent Multicast (PIM).
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:managed-kubernetes/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
