[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Also in 2005, Alistair Cockburn wrote about hexagonal architecture which is a software design pattern that is used along with the microservices.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] This pattern makes the design of the microservice possible since it isolates in layers the business logic from the auxiliary services needed in order to deploy and run the microservice completely independent from others.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Determining the appropriate level of (micro)service granularity in a microservices architecture often requires iterative collaboration between architects and developers.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] This process involves evaluating user requirements, service responsibilities, and architectural characteristics, such as non-functional requirements.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Neal Ford highlights the role of integrator and disintegrator factors in this context.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Integrator factors, such as shared transactions or tightly coupled processes, favor combining services, while disintegrator factors, such as fault tolerance or independent scalability, encourage splitting services to meet operational and architectural goals.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Additionally, fitness functions, as proposed by Neal Ford, can be used to validate architectural decisions and service granularity by continuously measuring system qualities or behaviors that are critical to stakeholders, ensuring alignment with overall architectural objectives.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] In microservices architectures, service granularity influences testing, deployment, performance, and reliability.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Very fine-grained microservices are typically easier to test and deploy independently, but they often experience lower performance and reduced overall reliability due to increased interservice communication and more complex service choreography.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Coarse-grained services exhibit contrasting characteristics.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] They generally provide higher robustness and reliability by minimizing communication overhead and coordination complexity, but they are more challenging to test and deploy because modifications affect a broader functional scope.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] The appropriate level of service granularity is determined by business drivers.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Architectural decisions commonly begin with identifying these drivers and then aligning architectural characteristics such as performance, scalability, reliability, or deployment flexibility to support them.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] A bounded context, a fundamental concept in domain-driven design (DDD), defines a specific area within which a domain model is consistent and valid, ensuring clarity and separation of concerns.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] In microservices architecture, a bounded context often maps to a microservice, but this relationship can vary depending on the design approach.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] A one-to-one relationship, where each bounded context is implemented as a single microservice, is typically ideal as it maintains clear boundaries, reduces coupling, and enables independent deployment and scaling.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] The choice of relationship should balance the principles of DDD with the system's business goals, technical constraints, and operational requirements.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] The architecture introduces additional complexity and new problems to deal with, such as latency, message format design, backup/availability/consistency (BAC), load balancing and fault tolerance.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] All of these problems have to be addressed at scale.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] The complexity of a monolithic application does not disappear if it is re-implemented as a set of microservices.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Some of the complexity gets translated into operational complexity.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Other places where the complexity manifests itself are increased network traffic and slower performance.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Also, an application made up of any number of microservices has a larger number of interface points to access its respective ecosystem, which increases the architectural complexity.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Various organizing principles (such as hypermedia as the engine of application state (HATEOAS), interface and data model documentation captured via Swagger, etc.) have been applied to reduce the impact of such additional complexity.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Microservices are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing – a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Ideally, microservices follow a "share-nothing" architecture.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] However, in practice, microservices architectures often encounter situations where code must be shared across services.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Each approach has its advantages and trade-offs, depending on the specific context and requirements.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] Richards & Ford in *Fundamentals of software architecture* (2020) propose each microservice should have its own architectural characteristics (a.k.a. non functional requirements), and architects should not define uniform characteristics for the entire distributed system.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] To avoid having to coordinate deployments across different microservices, Sam Newman suggests keeping the interfaces of microservices stable and making backwards-compatible changes as interfaces evolve.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] On the topic of testing, Newman in *Building Microservices* (2015) proposes consumer-driven contract testing as a better alternative to traditional end-to-end testing in the context of microservices.
[src:managed-kubernetes/microservices] He also suggests the use of log aggregation and metrics aggregation as well as distributed tracing tools to ensure the observability of systems composed of microservices.
